Lock the story's voice before any prose is written. The voice document is the
operational descendant of the vision: where the vision names a mood, the voice
makes concrete, checkable commitments every one of the {{ passage_count }} passages
must obey.

VISION: {{ vision.genre }}{% if vision.subgenre %} / {{ vision.subgenre }}{% endif %}, {{ vision.tone }}.
Themes: {{ vision.themes | join("; ") }}. Audience: {{ vision.audience }}.
POV hint (advisory): {{ vision.pov_hint or "none" }}.
PREMISE (the author's ask): {{ vision.premise }}

THE STORY'S SHAPE:
{% for d in dilemmas %}
- {{ d.question }} ({{ d.role }})
{% endfor %}
Endings: {{ endings | join(" / ") }}.

THE CAST (these spellings are canonical — any name the voice uses must match
one of them exactly):
{% for e in cast %}
- {{ e.name }}{% if e.pronouns %} ({{ e.pronouns }}){% endif %}: {{ e.concept }}
{% endfor %}

{% if research %}
CRAFT NOTES — voices and craft material from the author's corpus. Advisory, and
for the style exemplars among them a hard rule: they are a contrasting spread, a
map of the possibility space, never candidates — commit to a voice none of them
uses. If a decision below drifts toward sounding like one, move it. Never quote
or imitate a note's wording.

{{ research }}
{% endif %}
Decide:
- pov: whose head, how close — "second person", or "third person limited (NAME)"
  with NAME being the viewpoint character's name spelled exactly as the cast
  lists it. Never coin or vary a name here: every passage and its review will
  be held to this string verbatim.
- tense: past or present.
- diction: the register in a phrase ("spare, salt-worn, literary").
- rhythm: one line of sentence-rhythm rules.
- imagery: where the voice's images come from — the sensory domains it draws
  on and their limits ("tide, oil-light, worked rope; dread lives in objects,
  never in similes"). The writer reaches for this palette instead of copying
  phrasing it has seen, so make it generative: domains, not example sentences.
- dialogue: how speech behaves on the page — length, tags, what stays unsaid
  ("brief, unornamented; tags are 'said' or nothing").
- banned: 3-6 concrete patterns to forbid (punctuation habits, idiom classes,
  words that would puncture the tone).
- notes: one line of guidance for the writer.
